description:
Huge trunk with characteristic "alligator skin" texture. Leaves are deeply lobed with 6-10 round-tipped lobes. The upper side of each leaf is a dull green with minute hairs and has a soft, velvety texture. The underside of leaves is a pale green. Most leaves are about 2 inches long, but some are twice that length.  Branches droop. Long, conic acorns gradually taper to a pointed tip.

The tree is home to an abundance of wildlife. I've seen squirrels, honey bees, and many species of birds. 

The grand oaks in this park are hundreds of years old, according to the following reference: http://www.mercurynews.com/ci_23831692/silicon-valley-holdout-287-acre-farm-heart-sprawl

2016-08-01, added photos of acorns.

description:
This set of four shots is a photographic study of a Valley Oak that I photographed at Picchetti Ranch Open Space Preserve.  

Shot 1 shows this Valley Oak's leaves, backlit by the sun to emphasize their distintive shape:  obovate in outline, with many irregular, rounded lobes cutting deep into each leaf.  Black Oak (Quercus kelloggii) has similarly shaped leaves, but with lobes that are more squared off, rather than rounded.

Shot 2 most of the tree in situ, at the edge of Picchetti Pond.  I find it interesting that its main boughs are about as massive as its trunk.  Other large branches fork off from each main bough, creating the trees shady canopy.  

Shot 3 shows the Valley Oak's sturdy, central trunk.  Although this particular tree is still relatively young, it has already become quite a respectable tree.  As it grows older, it will likely become massive in stature, with a trunk that is several feet in diameter and forty feet or more in height.

Finally, Shot 4 shows the details of the bark on the trunk of a Valley Oak (Quercus lobata), which I photographed at Picchetti Ranch Open Space Preserve. The bark for this species of oak has a very rough, almost corrugated appearance.

Photographed at Picchetti Pond, Picchetti Ranch Open Space Preserve, near Cupertino, CA.

description:
Valley Oak (Quercus lobata), photographed at Murphy Park in Sunnyvale, CA.  This lead shot (Shot 1) shows the leaves of this tree, along with an acorn and a couple of acorn caps.  The leaves have the classic, deeply lobed shape that is distinctive for this species - so distinctive that it gave rise to its present-day scientific species name (lobata).  As Valley Oak is deciduous, its leaves have begun to exhibit patches of brown and golden, as they respond to the shorter days and cooler nights.

The single acorn shown in this picture is very large, over an inch long and around 3/4 of an inch in diameter at its widest point.  It is stoutly conical in shape and deeply chestnut brown in color, with a large, warty, light brown cap.  The acorns' large, bulky size are their most distinctive features.

Shot 2 provides a closeup iew of the tree's pewter gray bark.  The bark has a deeply corrugated, blocky texture to it, reminding me of the skin of a giant alligator.  Although other oak species have bark with a rough and rugged texture to it, none of them have bark that look quite like this.

Shot 3 provides a view of the tree's stout trunk, which is around three feet in diameter.  That is relatively modest for Valley Oaks, which can reach up to 9 feet in diameter with age. (This is probably still a relatively young tree.)

Finally, Shot 4 provides a view at the tree's canopy, as seen when one looks up into the canopy along the tree's trunk.  Note how the main branches of the tree twist and curl as they rise up into its canopy.  This is fairly typical of the species.  Valley Oaks are also known to develop a profusion of secondary branches and other growth that dangles down from the canopy, at time almost touching the ground;  this is why an old name for it is "weeping oak."  WIth this particular tree being planted in a city park, that kind of dangling growth is likely discouraged through the judicious use of pruning, for both safety and aesthetic reasons.

References:
1) Bruce M. Pavlik, et.al.  Oaks of California, Cachuma Press, Santa Barbara, pp. 10-12.
2) http://ucjeps.berkeley.edu/eflora, search for 'Quercus lobata.'

description: Durand White Oak observed in Cameron Park, near the Clubhouse, on a bluff high above the Brazos River valley at Waco TX.  This tree’s location is apparently very near another Durand Oak that was previously enrolled in the Texas Big Tree Registry (being State champion from Sep-2005 to May-2009, and last checked in Jun-2011) with these statistics: 117” trunk circumference, 51’ height, 63’ crown spread, for an Index of 183.  That tree is gone as of Dec-2018. Still another Durand Oak is found nearby right next to the Clubhouse. A Durand Oak prior champ (from Jun-1969) was also found in the Big Tree Registry about a quarter-mile southeast (near Proctor Springs), but that tree appears to have also died and was recently cut down; the two right-most photos show the reported location. Also at Proctor Springs, I observed two super large oaks (which appear to be White Oak, based on the leaves on the ground) and a modestly large Bur Oak, along with what I took to be several specimens of Durand Oak.  Obviously, Durand Oak is not uncommon in this area, although iNat users have not documented any others in the Brazos valley to date.

description:
INaturalist observation #3:
Family: Orchidaceae – Orchid family
Genus: Calypso Salisb. – fairy slipper
Species: Calypso bulbosa (L.) Oakes – fairy slipper

Calypso bulbosa (L.) Oakes / Venus'slipper: Low herb from a solid bulb with coralloid roots, producing a solitary basal leaf and a showy flower on a scape 5-15 cm high; leaf petiolate, the blade round-ovate, 2-4 cm long, acute at apex, rounded or subcordate at base; flower variegated, purple, pink and yellow; sepals and lateral petals 1-=15 mm long, ascending over the lip, pale purple; lip large, 15-20 mm long, saccate, whitish with purple markings, yellow-hairy within; column convex, bearing a lid-like anther just below the apex; pollinia 2 in each sac, united, all sessile on a broad gland. Coniferous forests.
Stems 5–20 cm, scapose with 2 sheathing bracts. Leaf basal, solitary, petiolate; blade glabrous, ovate, 3–6 cm long. Inflorescence a solitary flower subtended by a purplish, linear bract, 8–20 mm long. Flowers: sepals purple, lanceolate, 14–22 mm long, erect; upper 2 petals similar; lip petal forming a white- and purple-spotted pouch, ca. 2 cm long, open at the top, yellow within; margin of the orifice (lamina) bearded with paired horns near the front; column obovate, yellowish, hood-like over the lip. Capsule lanceoloid, 20–35 mm long. Dry to wet coniferous forest; valleys, montane. 
Foothills fescue subregion within the Grassland Natural Region. West of Claresholm within the Porcupine hills, Mixed wood forest, shaded by overstory . Southeast facing slope 4%. Eluviated eutric brunisolic soils of coarse textured mineral material. Mesa Butte, Birdseye, Crooked Creek soil series. Soil profile of Ah/Bf/Bm/Ck. 
Plant community: Antennaria anaphaloides, Polemonium pulcherrimum, Fragaria virginia, Arctostaphylos uva-ursi, Aspen, Pinus contorta.

description:
Valley Oak (Quercus lobata)

June 11, 2019
William B. Ide Adobe State Historic Park
Red Bluff, Tehama County, California

Valley Oak is an entirely endemic oak species to California and it grows heaviest in the northern and central parts of the state but extends its growth into southern California. The specimen from which we took these images was growing next to the Sacramento River in what is according to the iNat range map its most extensive area of growth. Valley Oak then is a native species to North America and to California specifically. See the range map here: https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/49011-Quercus-lobata

10 species of Oaks have been identified growing in Tehama County, California, according to the iNat archive. A careful comparison of the leaves of the oak we observed growing at the state park with those of all 10 species easily leads to the conclusion that ours is Valley Oak. The 10 oak species may be viewed here: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations?place_id=1530&subview=table&taxon_id=47851&view=species

description: It’s probably a bit of a miracle that this ancient Valley Oak has survived the Woolsey Fire. It was singed from below, but fire fighters must have extinguished the flames when they were defending the neighborhood 150 meters away. Other trees nearby didn’t fare that well; the whole area was devastated. I noticed lots of galls on the tree’s leaves, but it’s carrying plenty of large acorns, so is hopefully quite healthy. Around its stem were numerous burrow holes. As I was taking pictures, a California Ground Squirrel climbed down from the tree  and disappeared into one of them. I saw Western Honey Bees around and inside their hive on a charred branch, and finally an Acorn Woodpecker en route to this Valley Oak. Thank you fire fighters for saving it.

description:
A Valley Oak (Quercus lobata), photographed at Tree Life Cycles Park in east San Jose, CA.  Note that there are 9 photos in the set of pictures dpcumenting this tree:

Shot 1:  Distant shot of the tree, showing its height and breadth, as well as its general form.  Note the robustness of this tree's trunk and major boughs.

Shot 2:  A closeup of the bark covering this Valley Oak's trunk.  Note its rough, rugged, heavily creviced appearance and light gray color.

Shot 3:  A shot of this Valley Oak's canopy.  Note the robustness of its boughs and relative openness of its canopy.

Shot 4:  A shot of one of the leaves of this Valley Oak.

Shot 5:  A shot of more of this Valley Oak's leaves.  Some of the leaves in Shots 4 and 5 are broader or more irregularly shaped than is typical for a Valley Oak, so there may be some hybridization going on with it.

Shot 6 shows the gall of a Spined Turban Gall Wasp (Andricus douglasii), found growing on one of this Valley Oak's leaves.

Shot 7 shows the gall of a California Gall Wasp (Andricus quercuscalifornicus), found growing on one of this Valley Oak's branches.

Shot 8 shows the gall of a couple of Round Gall Wasp (Besbicus conspicuus), found growing on another of this Valley Oak's leaves.

Shot 9 shows the gall of a Convoluted Gall Wasp (Andricus confertus), found growing on another of this Valley Oak's leaves.

description:
A young Valley Oak (Quercus lobtata), photographed at Mocho Park in Livermore, CA.  Note that there are 5ve photos in the set of pictures documenting this specimen:

Shot 1:  Shows a set of leaves, whiich have the classic, deeply lobed, shape that Valley Oaks usually have.  Note the oblanceolate outline of these leaves and the deep sinus between the lobes.

Shot 2:  Shows the entire tree in situ along the banks of Arroyo Mocho Creek.  

Shot 3:  Shows the gall of a Convoluted Gall Wasp (Andricus confertus), which I discovered on one of this Valley Oak's leaves.

Shot 4:  Shows the gall of a California Gall Wasp (Andricus quercuscalifornicus) that was discovered attached to one of this Valley Oak's branches.

Shots 4 and 5:  Shows the galls of a couple of Red Cone Gall Wasps (Andricus kingi) on a couple of this Valley Oak's leaves.

description:
A month ago, I added these notes to https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/39751514 of a California Poppy: “The California Poppies I found at Paramount Ranch seemed stunted. None were taller than 15cm, most significantly shorter than that, around 7-10cm. The tips of leaves were already turning red. NPS Santa Monica Mountains tweeted a few days ago, “It's one of the driest winters in history (…) Anecdotally speaking & in general, growth of individual herbaceous (non-woody) plants appear to be smaller so far this season.” https://twitter.com/SantaMonicaMtns/status/1235678263957008384. These Poppies seemed to confirm their anecdotal assessment. 
Not anecdotal: California had its driest February in 126 years, according to NOAA. https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/monitoring-content/sotc/national/statewidepcpnrank/statewidepcpnrank-202002.png Drought has also returned. About one-third of California is in moderate drought, and nearly 70% is abnormally dry, according to https://droughtmonitor.unl.edu/.

What a difference a month can make. Not only (but most drastically) in terms of COVID-19. March and now April miracle rains have made these Poppies grow over 100cm tall on their way through Wild Oats and a Valley Oak seedling. YTD precipitation is now at 7.88 inches, with more to come over the next two days.

description: When I first saw this plant I thought it was a raspberry plant but it’s an blue elderberry plant. I noticed the leaves have a cleft (heart shape) form as they have small blades on the side of them. They are edible and can be used for jams, wine or syrups. The twigs can be used for basket weaving and for construction arrows. It also has a cultural significance where the tree is considered as Holy Tree that is capable of restoring good health and to promote long life. This tree is important ecologically as well because it’s the only host for an endangered Longhorn beetles that thrive on this tree. The Blue Elderberry tree have so many great qualities as it’s become beneficial to California and the surround states it grows in.

description:
QUICK BACKGROUND: 
It’s from the Apiaceae family which includes carrots, fennel, and parsley; it can be mistaken for such plants. When blooming, poison hemlock have white flowers while fennel have yellow flowers. It is a non-native and invasive plant in California.


GROWTH FORM:
- herb
- when young, it looks like a carrot plant


IDENTIFYING CHARACTERISTICS:
- stem: splotchy purple stems, no hair, hollow
- leaves: lobed, compound, alternate
- flowers: white flowers (at the time this plant was identified, the plant wasn’t blooming)


WHERE DOES IT GROW?: 
As long as there is enough water, poison hemlock can thrive in dry and wet places. The particular plant we saw grew near a river.


SIGNIFICANCE:
- poisonous!! All parts of the plant are poisonous, it’s even irritating to touch
- culturally significant: it’s what Socrates drank as poison to end his life
- ecologically significant: it’s poisonous to humans and cattle (animals) & it’s an invasive species

description:
Found this pretty flowering plant under the trees off a trail in the hills of Portola Valley, CA.  Fun facts about this plant are:

-"When hound’s tongue is flowering that is a sign that the morel mushrooms are also emerging from the low-elevation chaparral and oak woodland communities. Spring is on!"

-Native Americans made a preparation of the roots to treat burns and stomach aches.

Of the Borage family and scientifically known as Adelinia grande. It gets its name from the resemblance of its leaf shape to that of a dog’s tongue. It is native to western North America from southern British Columbia to San Luis Obispo county in California. In Oregon it occurs only on the west side of the Cascade Mountains, except in the Columbia River Gorge. 

 It is a perennial herb with bright blue/purple flowers and oval shaped leaves around the base of the plant.  The bright flowers attract bee pollinators.
